texts.label: paragraph
texts.orig: It's no secret that  Google Reader  is a popular way to keep up with your RSS feeds, but it's  getting shelved later this year . Most folks  suggested Feedly as a replacement  but I found the UI quite clunky in a browser and on Android devices.
texts.text: It's no secret that  Google Reader  is a popular way to keep up with your RSS feeds, but it's  getting shelved later this year . Most folks  suggested Feedly as a replacement  but I found the UI quite clunky in a browser and on Android devices.

texts.label: paragraph
texts.orig: Then someone suggested  Tiny Tiny RSS . I couldn't learn more about it on the day Google Reader's shutdown was announced because the site was slammed. In a nutshell, Tiny Tiny RSS is a well-written web UI for managing feeds and a handy API for using it with mobile applications. The backend code is written in PHP and it supports MySQL and Postgres.
texts.text: Then someone suggested  Tiny Tiny RSS . I couldn't learn more about it on the day Google Reader's shutdown was announced because the site was slammed. In a nutshell, Tiny Tiny RSS is a well-written web UI for managing feeds and a handy API for using it with mobile applications. The backend code is written in PHP and it supports MySQL and Postgres.

texts.label: paragraph
texts.orig: There's also an  Android application  that gives you a seven day trial once you install it. The  pro key costs $1.99 .
texts.text: There's also an  Android application  that gives you a seven day trial once you install it. The  pro key costs $1.99 .

texts.label: paragraph
texts.orig: The installation took me a few minutes and then I was off to the races. I'd recommend implementing SSL for accessing your installation (unless you like passing credentials in the clear) and enable keepalive connections in Apache. The UI in the application drags down a ton of javascript as it works and enabling keepalives will keep your page load times low.
